\newcommandx*{\triplearrow}[4][1=0, 2=1]{
	% #1 = shorten left (optional), #2 = shorten right (optionsl),
	% #3 = draw options (must contain arrow type), #4 = path
  	\draw[line width=\myline,double distance=3\myline,#3] #4;
  	\draw[line width=\myline,shorten <=#1\myline,shorten >=#2\myline,#3] #4;
}

\section{Introduction}

$\mathsf{Semantics}\dashv\mathsf{Syntax}$ relationships between some
notion of type theory\footnote{or, more broadly, some formal language}
and some flavor of category abound. They range from the well known
and well studied example of the internal language of a topos, to linear
type theory and $\star$-autonomous categories, to regular type theory
for regular categories, among many others\footnote{As Shulman points out, a far more complete list can be found in Part
D of ``The Elephant''} and more recent developments, e.g. homtopy type theory, cubical type
theory, etc. have extended this library of $\mathsf{Semantics}\dashv\mathsf{Syntax}$
relationships into higher category theory.

But what makes such a relationship, and therefor a type theory \emph{practical}?
Can we conjecture some criteria which judge a particular $\mathsf{Semantics}\dashv\mathsf{Syntax}$
relationship well adapted, both in strength and sensibility, to reasoning
about that flavor of category in general?

In
\begin{quotation}
``A Practical Type Theory for Symmetric Monoidal Categories''
\end{quotation}
Mike Shulman develops such a list of criteria and then follows them
towards a new type theory for symmetric monoidal categories, $\mathsf{PTT}$.

\subsection{The Criteria}

While Shulman provides a longer list for the specific case of symmetric
monoidal categories, two items provide a more general principle. Any
practical $\text{\ensuremath{\mathsf{Semantics}\dashv\mathsf{Syntax}} relationship }$
should enjoy:
\begin{enumerate}
\item an initiality theorem:
\begin{enumerate}
\item say something nice here
\item $\mathsf{Semantics\left(\mathsf{Syntax}\left(\sC\right)\right)\liso\sC}$;
and
\end{enumerate}
\item possess term and typing judgements which permit us to reason about
types as ``sets with elements'', albeit with some carefully chosen
restrictions, e.g. coherence, linearity, etc.).
\end{enumerate}
In this blog post we'll :
\begin{itemize}
\item try to convince you that these requirements, while simple to state,
are far  more sophisticated than they might appear;
\item we'll follow them towards a syntax for symmetric monoidal categories,
indeed we'll see precisely how these two requirements almost innevitably
lead to Shulman's $\mathsf{PTT}$ as a synthesis of Sweedler's notation
and Street\&Batanin's Computads
\item we'll explore a specific instance of Shulman's practical type theory,
and see how these requirements play out;
\item ; and more
\item in this last point we'll suggest a little of the direction of the
ACT project.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Initiality}

What are we talking about when we talk about categories with type
theory?

\subsection{Sets With Elements}

The great surge in interest in the relationship between type theory
and category theory has, of course, been spurred by the advent of
homotopy type theory. In particular, homotopy type theory has shown
how particular principled choices in a syntax for elementary reasoning
can be used to reason about structures which are far from discrete.
\footnote{It should of course be noted that synthetic geometry set the stage
for such a PROGRAM as it demonstrates very well that a sophisticated
treatment of elements can in fact}

----THIS NEEDS FIXING----

While the parametrization of $\mathsf{HoTT}$ by $\left(\infty,1\right)$-toposes
is present in the library of higher inductive types which are put
into the theory as primitive rules; every $\left(\infty,1\right)$-topos
is locally presentable, meaning it is the

While $\mathsf{HoTT}$ thereby justifies our interest in such a relationship
for symmetric monoidal categories, the character of such categories
is in general, very different than the character of $\left(\infty,1\right)$-toposes
and indeed 1-toposes.

Typing judgements are.. such they should be maps

While $\times$ enjoys a universal property characterized in terms
of projection maps, the universal property of $\otimes$ is characterized
in terms of co-projection maps. In particular, for any $z\in X\times Y$,
we have that 
\[
z=\mathsf{pair}\left(\pr_{1}\left(z\right),\pr_{2}\left(z\right)\right)
\]
 whereas no such characterization of the elements of $X\otimes Y$
is available. Locating the concern in the familiar terrain of vector
spaces provides this categorical phenomenon with concrete intuition;
it is the fact that the tensor product $\bigotimes_{i\in\left\{ 1,\dots,n\right\} }V_{i}$
of vector spaces is comrised not of simple tensors 
\[
v=v_{1}\otimes\cdots\otimes v_{n}=\mathsf{tuple}\left(v_{1},\dots,v_{n}\right)
\]
but of linear combinations of them. Any \emph{practical }type theory
for symmetric monoidal categories

We can however, pretend that every tensor is a tuple, provided we
are very careful; this is exactly the power of Sweedler's notation
which Shulman's expands into a syntax.
